Part 1: Basic simulation and NHST

Lets start by convincing ourselves that t-tests have the appropriate false positive rate. Run 10,000 t-tests with standard, normally-distributed data from a made up 30-person, single-measurement experiment (the command for sampling from a normal distribution is rnorm). Whats the mean number of significant results?

First do this using a for loop.

n = 10000
false_positive_count <- 0
for (i in 1:n) {
  d <- rnorm(30)
  false_positive_count = false_positive_count + as.integer(t.test(d, mu = 0)$p.value <0.05)
}
mean_significant <- false_positive_count / n

mean_significant
## [1] 0.0493

Next, do this using the replicate function:

significance_propostion <- sum(replicate(n, as.integer(t.test(rnorm(30), mu = 0)$p.value <0.05))) / n
significance_propostion
## [1] 0.049

Ok, that was a bit boring. Lets try something moderately more interesting - lets implement a p-value sniffing simulation, in the style of Simons, Nelson, & Simonsohn (2011).

Consider this scenario: you have done an experiment, again with 30 participants (one observation each, just for simplicity). The question is whether their performance is above chance. You arent going to check the p-value every trial, but lets say you run 30 - then if the p-value is within the range p < .25 and p > .05, you optionally run 30 more and add those data, then test again. But if the original p value is < .05, you call it a day, and if the original is > .25, you also stop.

First, write a function that implements this sampling regime.

double.sample <- function (first_sample) {
  current_p <- t.test(first_sample, mu = 0)$p.value
  if (current_p > 0.05 && current_p <= 0.25) {
    first_sample <- c(first_sample, rnorm(length(first_sample)))
  }
  return (first_sample)
}

Now call this function 10k times and find out what happens.

significance_propostion_doube <- sum(replicate(n, as.integer(t.test(double.sample(rnorm(30)), mu = 0)$p.value <0.05))) / n
significance_propostion_doube
## [1] 0.0686

Is there an inflation of false positives? How bad is it?

Answer: The inflation of false positives under the null is important but not drastic. From 5% to 7.08%

Now modify this code so that you can investigate this double the sample rule in a bit more depth. Lets see what happens when you double the sample ANY time p > .05 (not just when p < .25), or when you do it only if p < .5 or < .75. How do these choices affect the false positive rate?

HINT: Try to do this by making the function double.sample take the upper p value as an argument, so that you can pass this through dplyr.

HINT 2: You may need more samples. Find out by looking at how the results change from run to run.

# The parameters of this function can determine the alpha level as well as the upper p value that represents the threshold below which the experiment is re-ran by doubling the sample size.
double.sample <- function (first_sample, lp, up) {
  current_p <- t.test(first_sample, mu = 0)$p.value
  if (current_p > lp && current_p <= up) {
    first_sample <- c(first_sample, rnorm(length(first_sample)))
  }
  return (first_sample)
}

# Always double the number of samples as long as it does not pass the first significance test.
n = 100000
sample_size = 30
lp = 0.01
significance_propostion_always <- sum(replicate(n, as.integer(t.test(double.sample(rnorm(sample_size), lp, 1), mu = 0)$p.value < lp))) / n
significance_propostion_always
## [1] 0.01734
# Only double it if you have p > 0.05 and p <= 0.75
significance_propostion_75 <- sum(replicate(n, as.integer(t.test(double.sample(rnorm(sample_size), lp, .75), mu = 0)$p.value < lp))) / n
significance_propostion_75
## [1] 0.01737

What do you conclude on the basis of this simulation? How bad is this kind of data-dependent policy?

Answer: When you always double the data (if it wasnt significant on the first pass), the false positive rate goes up to 8.4%. When you double it only when the first p-value is below 0.75 and above 0.05, the false positive rate drops to 8.2%.

Not a drastic effect, but it certainly undermines the purpose of using significance testing. If the significance level alpha is chose to be 0.01 the proportion of resulting false positivies versus supposed false positives inceases (it results in 1.85% false positive rate, which is a ratio of 1.85, compared to 1.678). In a way the problem becomes more severe when we increase the significance level (reduce the alpha to something closer to zero), so that may not be a good policy approach to side-stepping this issue.

Thought question: Take a moment to interpret the coefficients of the model. Q1 - What are the units? Q2 - How does the interaction relate to the plot? Q3 - Should there be an interaction in the model? What does it mean? How important is it?

Answer 1: It seems that the semantics of the model change. Thats because the OJ now seems to be taking the role of the intercept (it registers exactly the same coefficient as the intercept). The only variable that has a different coefficient now is the Vitamin C. This is the case whether or not there is an interaction term. A drastic change is the overall R-squared, which increases when you remove the intercept (I find it hard to explain this fact, given that you have more variables with the intercept).

Answer 2: It seems that the intercept is simply being reproduced by employing the variable OJ instead. The correction in the coefficient for VC may be to adjust the slope to produce a near identical model.

Answer 3: The interaction only seems to add about 0.01 to the R^2 (and to the adjusted R^2). I suspect that the overfitting effects of such an increase may not be worth the marginal increase in the R^2.

The dataset here is from Stiller, Goodman, & Frank (2014), a paper on childrens pragmatic inferences. We saw the paradigm in the counterbalancing lecture: its three faces: a smiley, a smiley with glasses, and a smiley with a hat and glasses. When told my friend has glasses do kids pick the one with the glasses and no hat? age.group is the kids age group, condition is either label, described above, or no label, which was a control condition in which kids picked without hearing the term glasses at all.

Brief Confidence Interval Digression

Start out by setting up a function for a 95% CI using the normal approximation.

ci95.norm <- function(x) {
  st_of_x <- sd(x)
  up.ci <- mean(x) + st_of_x*qnorm(.975)
  down.ci <- mean(x) - st_of_x*qnorm(.975)
  down_and_up <- c(down.ci, up.ci)
  return (down_and_up)
}

But the number of participants in a group is likely to be < 30, so lets also compute this with a t distribution.

ci95.t <- function(x) {
  low.ci <- mean(x) + qt(.025, length(x) - 1)
  high.ci <- mean(x) + qt(.975, length(x) - 1)
  together <- c(low.ci, high.ci)
  return (together)
}

On the other hand, maybe we should use bootstrap CIs because these are actually proportions, and the normal/t approximations dont know that they are 0/1 bounded.

Take a look at ?boot and ?bootci. Note that the syntax for the boot library is terrible, so were going to use it to check some code that I use:

theta <- function(x,xdata,na.rm=T) {mean(xdata[x],na.rm=na.rm)}
ci.low <- function(x,na.rm=T) {
  mean(x,na.rm=na.rm) - 
    quantile(bootstrap(1:length(x),
                       10000,theta,x,na.rm=na.rm)$thetastar,.025,na.rm=na.rm)}
ci.high <- function(x,na.rm=T) {
  quantile(bootstrap(1:length(x),
                     10000,theta,x,na.rm=na.rm)$thetastar,.975,na.rm=na.rm) - 
    mean(x,na.rm=na.rm)}

Now make 95% confidence intervals across participants using all the methods above:

On to linear mixed effect models. Create the maximal random effects model a la Barr et al. (2013). Does it converge? If not, what will you do to make it converge? (The internet can be your friend here).

HINT: try simplifying your model to a semi-maximal model. Bonus: try using a different fitting procedure on the maximal model.

HINT: make sure that you consider which random effects are appropriate. Consider which observations are within/between subjects. E.g. having a random coefficient for age by subject doesnt make sense, because each subject has only one age.

lme.model <- lmer(correct ~ age.group + condition + (1|subid), data = d)
